{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-topic-topic-tsx","path":"/topics/childhood-cancers-recognition-referral/","result":{"data":{"firstChapter":{"id":"3a84248b-68fe-535d-a2c8-570960c744af","slug":"summary","fullItemName":"Summary","subChapters":[],"depth":1,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field 616bbb43-864b-4234-9e6b-b06fa06e5808 --><h1>Childhood cancers - recognition and referral: Summary</h1><!-- end field 616bbb43-864b-4234-9e6b-b06fa06e5808 -->","htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item ca8026e7-cc75-4940-9845-e3e999508b1f --><!-- begin field 5fa39ed9-8a8a-498d-95fc-4bd4547050a5 --><ul><li>Neuroblastoma<ul><li>Neuroblastoma is a rare cancer, generally occurring in young children.</li><li>It is the commonest cancer in the first year of life, though there are only around 100 cases annually in the UK.</li><li>The 5 year survival is between 50–90%.</li><li>Consider very urgent referral (for an appointment within 48 hours) for specialist assessment for neuroblastoma in children with a palpable abdominal mass or unexplained enlarged abdominal organ.</li><li> Retinoblastoma<ul><li>Retinoblastoma is a very rare cancer, almost all occurring in young children.</li><li>Around 50 cases occur annually in the UK.</li><li>The 5 year survival is almost 100%.</li><li>The symptoms include an abnormal reflection through the pupil, which appears white rather than red.</li><li>Consider urgent referral (for an appointment within 2 weeks) for ophthalmological assessment for retinoblastoma in children with an absent red reflex.</li></ul></li><li>Wilms’ tumour is a very rare cancer of childhood, affecting the kidney.<ul><li style=\"list-style-type: none;\"><ul><li>It is an embryonal tumour, though usually affects children aged 1–3 years.</li><li>Fewer than 50 cases occur in the UK annually.</li><li>The 5 year survival is approximately 90%.</li><li>Wilms’ tumour usually presents with an abdominal mass, sometimes accompanied by pain or haematuria.</li><li>Consider very urgent referral (for an appointment within 48 hours) for specialist assessment for Wilms' tumour in children with any of the following:<ul><li>A palpable abdominal mass.</li><li>An unexplained enlarged abdominal organ.</li><li>Unexplained visible haematuria.</li></ul></li></ul></li></ul></li></ul></li></ul><!-- end field 5fa39ed9-8a8a-498d-95fc-4bd4547050a5 --><!-- end item ca8026e7-cc75-4940-9845-e3e999508b1f -->","topic":{"id":"7ea64737-af89-5cad-8f33-2466d98eab3a","topicId":"360677c6-0adf-45e4-87f1-98b0ab02c557","topicName":"Childhood cancers - recognition and referral","slug":"childhood-cancers-recognition-referral","aliases":[],"chapters":[{"id":"3a84248b-68fe-535d-a2c8-570960c744af","slug":"summary","fullItemName":"Summary","subChapters":[]},{"id":"6172d98b-b3d3-59d4-bfcb-f0d787673884","slug":"have-i-got-the-right-topic","fullItemName":"Have I got the right topic?","subChapters":[]},{"id":"82d59d36-e24e-5089-8870-952cec58c93b","slug":"how-up-to-date-is-this-topic","fullItemName":"How up-to-date is this topic?","subChapters":[{"id":"951de1cf-297e-5e28-90f7-2b482a3f73d4","slug":"changes","fullItemName":"Changes"},{"id":"93b60b97-3e26-5b64-a493-791a75266270","slug":"update","fullItemName":"Update"}]},{"id":"43a3c8ca-4187-59d9-b1af-842bda4159f8","slug":"goals-outcome-measures","fullItemName":"Goals and outcome measures","subChapters":[{"id":"311645ef-ef46-5c04-a220-135331185f90","slug":"goals","fullItemName":"Goals"},{"id":"25f3b274-a4d7-5071-9854-87246c3a13d6","slug":"outcome-measures","fullItemName":"Outcome measures"},{"id":"d04c3c26-8145-5dd2-9e26-642ebe9403d7","slug":"audit-criteria","fullItemName":"Audit criteria"},{"id":"2ae9f6b6-9722-5f17-b601-6f5ca8bbc2eb","slug":"qof-indicators","fullItemName":"QOF indicators"},{"id":"6ea5d6b9-bf9c-5af9-a190-d7e85fff8f9e","slug":"qipp-options-for-local-implementation","fullItemName":"QIPP - Options for local implementation"},{"id":"c18ccf4b-f36f-5964-9349-a4df758477cf","slug":"nice-quality-standards","fullItemName":"NICE quality standards